Mauritius and other countries for the first time found cases of infection of the Omicron strain - Xinhua Xinhua News Agency Beijing, Dec. 12 (Xinhua) - Comprehensive Xinhua News Agency overseas correspondents reported: Mauritius, Cyprus and Malawi recently reported for the first time found cases of infection of the Omicron strain of the new crown variant virus. Mauritius reported for the first time two cases of Omicron strain infection in the country on the 10th. According to the Minister of Health Kailash Jagutpal, an infected person was a tourist who arrived in Mauritius on November 27 from South Africa; another infected person was a local resident of Mauritius who tested positive for nucleic acid on November 30 after coming into contact with a person who had recently returned from a trip to South Africa. After isolation in hospital, both infected persons tested negative for nucleic acid and have now returned to their respective places of residence. The Cyprus Ministry of Health announced on the 10th that three cases of infection with the Omicron strain were diagnosed for the first time in the country. These three people are students, returned from a trip abroad earlier this month, due to all the mild disease, not admitted to hospital. To prevent the spread of the Omicron strain, the Serbian government has been increasing its prevention and control efforts. From December 6 to January 10 next year, passengers over 12 years old who arrive by air are required to undergo nucleic acid testing at the airport at their own expense. The Serbian Ministry of Health also announced on the 10th that it will start vaccinating children between the ages of 5 and 11 with the Pfizer New Crown vaccine. Malawi's Health Minister Kumbize Chibunda said on September 9 that three cases of infection with the Omicron strain were found in the country for the first time. The country's health department carried out genome sequencing of 12 new crown-positive samples collected from Nov. 9 to Dec. 2, and found the three cases of infection.
